# Testing

## Framework

Vitest only. Never use Jest — the configs are different and pnpm workspace
requires a single test runner.

## Test Coverage Requirements

For every new function or class:
- At least one happy-path test
- At least one failure-mode test (invalid input, API error, network error)
- Edge cases: empty arrays, maximum amounts, null vs undefined, boundary dates

## Test Naming Conventions

Use descriptive names in domain language. Japanese names are encouraged where
they improve clarity:

```typescript
// ✅ Clear domain language
it('特例期間中（適法）の場合、給与振込を実行する', async () => { ... });

// ✅ Regression guard with reason
it("rejects shorui '21' at compile time (regression: was Day 1 bug)", () => {
  // @ts-expect-error — shorui must be '11' | '12'
  generateZenginFile({ shorui: '21' as never });
});

// ❌ Vague
it('works', () => { ... });
it('test 1', () => { ... });
```

## Fixtures Organization

Banking test fixtures in `fixtures/{bank-name}-sample-{purpose}.dat`.
Each fixture file must begin with a comment citing the source:

```
// Source: 全銀協標準通信プロトコル仕様書 第X版 p.XX
// https://www.zengin-net.or.jp/...
```

## Snapshot Tests

For Zengin file output, use buffer equality — NOT snapshot files:

```typescript
expect(result.buffer).toEqual(expected); // ✅ Deterministic
expect(result.buffer.toString('hex')).toMatchSnapshot(); // ❌ Encoding-dependent
```

## Mocking

For HTTP calls, use Vitest's `vi.spyOn` on `undici.fetch`, or inject a mock
`HttpClient` via the constructor. Never mock `global.fetch` directly.

For token storage, use `InMemoryTokenStorage` in tests.

## Compile-time Error Tests

Use `@ts-expect-error` to assert type-level rejections:

```typescript
// @ts-expect-error — shorui '21' must not compile
generateZenginFile({ shorui: '21' });
```

If the `@ts-expect-error` causes a typecheck error (no error was produced),
the type guard regressed — fail immediately.

## Test File Location

Co-locate tests with source: `src/foo.ts` → `src/__tests__/foo.test.ts`
or `src/foo.test.ts`. Either is acceptable; be consistent within a package.
